label.value: increased proteasome localization to nuclear periphery

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a proteasome to the nuclear periphery is increased.

label.value: decreased level of histone H2A in cell

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of histone H2A measured in the cell is lower than normal.
A phenotype in which a transcript, i.e. an RNA molecule synthesized on a DNA template by RNA polymerase, is shorter than normal.
A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein oligomerization is abnormal.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which protein oligomerization is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: decreased histone H3 localization to chromatin at protein coding gene

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of histone H3 to chromatin at one or more protein-coding genes is decreased.

label.value: decreased histone H2B localization to chromatin at protein coding gene

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of histone H2B to chromatin at one or more protein-coding genes is decreased.

label.value: increased histone H3-K4 dimethylation during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the dimethylation of lysine at position 4 of histone H3 occurs to a greater extent than normal.

label.value: decreased level of ubiquitinated protein in cell

value.value: A cell phenotype in which the amount of ubiquitinated protein measured the cell is lower than normal when the cell is in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle. Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal level of ubiquitinated protein in cell

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of ubiquitinated protein measured in a cell is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). Total protein or a specific protein may be affected.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing doxorubicin.

label.value: decreased transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter during vegetative growth

value.value: A cellular process phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which transcription from one or more RNA polymerase II promoters occurs to a lower extent than normal.

label.value: normal regulation of translation in response to UV

value.value: A gene expression phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which regulation of translation in response to ultraviolet light is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

label.value: loss of viability in stationary phase upon glucose starvation

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a smaller than normal proportion of cells in the population remains viable after entering stationary phase, when cells the population are subject to glucose starvation.

definition.value: Use this term to annotate experiments in which a culture is grown to stationary phase, and then the number of cells viable enough to form a colony upon return to conditions supporting vegetative growth is measured and compared to wild type. Note that FYPO uses "glucose starvation" to refer specifically to conditions in which glucose is scarce enough to trigger mating, meiosis, and sporulation. For phenotypes observed in the presence of enough glucose to prevent cells from mating, use a term that specifies "during vegetative growth" plus a condition to indicate low glucose.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to a protein complex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The protein whose binding to the protein complex is assayed may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with a protein complex that is assayed in a mutant, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which the binding of one protein to an MCM complex is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type). The protein whose binding to the MCM complex is assayed may be encoded by the mutated gene, or may be encoded by a different gene.

definition.value: This term can be used for any interaction with a protein complex that is assayed in a mutant, whether or not the mutated gene product is one of the interacting proteins. We recommend noting which proteins were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A molecular function phenotype in which MCM complex binding by a gene product (usually a protein) in a mutant does not occur. The affected gene product may be encoded by the mutated gene, or by a different gene.

label.value: abolished protein localization to chromatin at stalled replication fork

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at stalled replication forks is abolished.

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

label.value: normal protein localization to chromatin at stalled replication fork

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the localization of a protein to chromatin at stalled replication forks is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type).

definition.value: We recommend noting which protein(s) were used in the assay when annotating to this term.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-proline measured in a cell is higher than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-tryptophan measured in a cell is higher than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-tyrosine measured in a cell is higher than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-tryptophan measured in the cell is lower than normal.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-tyrosine measured in the cell is lower than normal.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on glutamine nitrogen source

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing glutamine as the nitrogen source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: increased cell population growth on glutamine nitrogen source

value.value: A vegetative cell population phenotype in which cell growth is increased relative to normal in a medium containing glutamine as the nitrogen source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on arabinose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing arabinose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: increased cell population growth on arabinose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is increased relative to normal in a medium containing arabinose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: decreased cell population growth on melibiose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is decreased relative to normal in a medium containing melibiose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: increased cell population growth on melibiose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is increased relative to normal in a medium containing melibiose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

value.value: An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of tellurite (TeO3(2-)) ions than normal.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of caesium ions than normal.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to caesium ions. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of caesium ions that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to tellurite (TeO3(2-)) ions. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of tellurite ions that allows wild type cells to grow.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to tamoxifen. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of tamoxifen that allows wild type cells to grow.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of tamoxifen than normal.
A phenotype in which vegetative cell population growth is normal (i.e. indistinguishable from wild type) in a medium containing tamoxifen.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a carboxypeptidase activity is abnormal.
A molecular function phenotype in which the observed rate of a carboxypeptidase activity is decreased.
A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-proline measured in the cell is lower than normal.

label.value: increased cell population growth at high temperature

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which the growth of a population of cells is increased relative to normal in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle at high temperatures.

definition.value: For fission yeast, high temperature usually corresponds to above 32 degrees Celsius. Use this term if you have assayed growth of cells exposed to heat in culture. If you have assayed the response to heat at the subcellular or molecular level, consider annotating to 'abnormal cellular response to heat' (FYPO:0000212).

label.value: increased cell density in stationary phase

value.value: A cell population phenotype in which a population reaches stationary phase at, and maintains, a higher cell density than wild type.

label.value: increased cell population growth at low temperature

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is increased relative to normal at a low temperature.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise. For fission yeast, low temperature usually corresponds to below 25 degrees Celsius.

label.value: increased cell population growth on galactose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is increased relative to normal in a medium containing galactose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

label.value: increased cell population growth on maltose carbon source

value.value: A vegetative cell population growth phenotype in which cell growth is increased relative to normal in a medium containing maltose as the carbon source.

definition.value: Note that cell growth terms refer to growth under aerobic conditions unless stated otherwise.

value.value: A cell phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which the amount of L-arginine measured in a cell is higher than normal.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of dithiothreitol than normal.
An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of lead ions than normal.

An increased chemical resistance phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells grow in the presence of a higher concentration of sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS) than normal.

A phenotype observed in the vegetative growth phase of the life cycle in which cells show increased sensitivity to aluminium ions. Cells stop growing (and may die) at a concentration of aluminium ions that allows wild type cells to grow.
